Hi ! 
I liked this puzzle, but I agree with IGPro : I don't know why, when the final result is exactly an integer, should we keep one non-signifying zero ? 

Here's my Javascript code (I had to do some wierd stuff in the end to be able to suit this specific situation, but I think it would be better without non significant 0 if integer result)

const x = parseInt(readline());
const n = parseInt(readline());
let sum = 0;
let f = 1;

for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    sum += Math.pow(x, i) / (i ? f *= i : 1);
}

let result = Math.floor(sum * 1e5) / 1e5;
console.log(Number.isInteger(result) ? result.toFixed(1) : result.toString().replace(/\.?0+$/, ''));
